{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775857632511,"sessionID":"ses_286a45da0ffejuCyw3IPOkmwxR","part":{"id":"prt_d795d0107001lW64ha2DiEs8Z1","messageID":"msg_d795cf70d001DsoSNFgZVtEaXx","sessionID":"ses_286a45da0ffejuCyw3IPOkmwxR","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_805a7516e0f64379a98762f0","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/proposal.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/proposal.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Proposal: AR-017 — PicoD JWT 中间件增强\n2: \n3: ## Summary\n4: \n5: Enhance the existing JWT authentication middleware in `pkg/picod` with configurable public paths, dynamic public key rotation, and flexible token extraction. The enhancement improves the current auth.go implementation to better support production deployment scenarios.\n6: \n7: ## Purpose\n8: \n9: ### Background\n10: \n11: The current PicoD service (AR-015) includes basic JWT authentication via `AuthManager` in `pkg/picod/auth.go`. The implementation loads an RSA public key from the `PICOD_AUTH_PUBLIC_KEY` environment variable and validates Bearer tokens on all `/api/*` endpoints. However, the current implementation lacks:\n12: \n13: - Public path configuration (endpoints that don't require authentication)\n14: - Dynamic public key rotation without service restart\n15: - Support for token extraction via query parameters\n16: - Granular error handling matching the router package patterns\n17: \n18: ### Goal\n19: \n20: Enhance the PicoD JWT middleware in `pkg/picod` with:\n21: - Configurable public paths via environment variable\n22: - Dynamic public key hot-reload via SIGHUP signal\n23: - Optional query parameter token support\n24: - Consistent error response format with error codes\n25: \n26: ### Value\n27: - Production-ready authentication with flexible configuration\n28: - Zero-downtime public key rotation for security operations\n29: - Support for API clients that prefer query parameter token passing\n30: - Consistency with the router package error handling patterns\n31: \n32: ---\n33: \n34: ## Scope\n35: \n36: ### In-Scope\n37: \n38: | Deliverable | Description |\n39: |-------------|-------------|\n40: | Public path configuration | Environment variable `PICOD_AUTH_PUBLIC_PATHS` for exempt endpoints |\n41: | Dynamic key reload | SIGHUP signal handler to reload public key without restart |\n42: | Query parameter support | Environment variable `PICOD_AUTH_ALLOW_QUERY_PARAM` to enable token in URL |\n43: | Error response standardization | Consistent `error_code` field in error responses |\n44: | Configuration struct | AuthConfig for middleware options |\n45: \n46: ### Configuration\n47: \n48: | Variable | Required | Default | Description |\n49: |----------|----------|---------|-------------|\n50: | PICOD_AUTH_PUBLIC_KEY | Yes | - | PEM-encoded RSA public key |\n51: | PICOD_AUTH_PUBLIC_PATHS | No | /health | Comma-separated paths that skip auth |\n52: | PICOD_AUTH_ALLOW_QUERY_PARAM | No | false | Enable token via ?token= query param |\n53: | PICOD_JWT_ISSUER | No | - | Expected JWT issuer claim |\n54: | PICOD_JWT_AUDIENCE | No | - | Expected JWT audience claim |\n55: \n56: ### Code Structure\n57: \n58: ```\n59: pkg/picod/\n60: ├── auth.go           # Existing AuthManager (to be enhanced)\n61: ├── auth_config.go   # NEW: AuthConfig struct and loading\n62: ├── auth_middleware.go  # NEW: Enhanced middleware with options\n63: ├── server.go        # Updated: Use new middleware with config\n64: └── main.go          # No changes needed\n65: ```\n66: \n67: ### Out-of-Scope\n68: - Token refresh/reissue endpoints\n69: - Rate limiting on auth failures\n70: - Login endpoint implementation\n71: - Multi-tenant namespace isolation\n72: \n73: ---\n74: \n75: ## Impact Analysis\n76: \n77: ### Dependencies\n78: \n79: | Dependency | Source | Purpose |\n80: |------------|--------|---------|\n81: | github.com/gin-gonic/gin | existing | HTTP framework |\n82: | github.com/golang-jwt/jwt/v5 | existing | JWT validation |\n83: | k8s.io/klog/v2 | existing | Logging |\n84: | os/signal (stdlib) | existing | SIGHUP handling |\n85: \n86: ### Upstream\n87: \n88: - **AR-015 PicoD Service** — Existing authentication foundation\n89: - **pkg/router/jwt_middleware.go** — Reference implementation patterns\n90: \n91: ### Downstream Consumers\n92: \n93: 1. **Code Execution Clients** — Must provide valid JWT in Authorization header\n94: 2. **File Management Clients** — Same auth requirements\n95: 3. **Monitoring Systems** — May use /health without auth\n96: \n97: ### Risks\n98: \n99: | Risk | Severity | Mitigation |\n100: |------|----------|------------|\n101: | Key rotation race condition | Medium | RWMutex for key access during reload |\n102: | Query param token leakage | Medium | Disable by default, warn in docs |\n103: | Invalid public key reload | Low | Validate new key before replacing, rollback on failure |\n104: \n105: ---\n106: \n107: ## Alternatives Considered\n108: \n109: ### Option 1: Current Implementation (Baseline)\n110: \n111: **Approach**: Keep existing auth.go as-is without enhancements.\n112: \n113: **Pros**:\n114: - No code changes required\n115: - Stable and tested\n116: - Simpler to maintain\n117: \n118: **Cons**:\n119: - No public path flexibility\n120: - Requires service restart for key rotation\n121: - No query param support\n122: \n123: **Decision**: Not selected — insufficient for production operations.\n124: \n125: ---\n126: \n127: ### Option 2: Full Integration with Router Package (Selected)\n128: \n129: **Approach**: Create auth_config.go and auth_middleware.go in pkg/picod, using patterns from pkg/router/jwt_middleware.go.\n130: \n131: **Pros**:\n132: - Consistent error handling with router package\n133: - Public path configuration support\n134: - Dynamic key rotation\n135: - Query parameter support option\n136: \n137: **Cons**:\n138: - Additional code to maintain\n139: - Slight increase in complexity\n140: \n141: **Decision**: Selected — balances flexibility with maintainability.\n142: \n143: ---\n144: \n145: ### Option 3: Use External Auth Service\n146: \n147: **Approach**: Delegate authentication to an external service (e.g., OAuth2 proxy).\n148: \n149: **Pros**:\n150: - Offloads auth complexity\n151: - Standard auth flows (OAuth2, OIDC)\n152: - Centralized key management\n153: \n154: **Cons**:\n155: - Additional infrastructure dependency\n156: - Network latency for auth checks\n157: - Not aligned with current architecture\n158: \n159: **Decision**: Deferred — future consideration if multi-tenant requirements emerge.\n160: \n161: ---\n162: \n163: ## Implementation Plan\n164: \n165: ### Phase 1: Configuration Support\n166: - [ ] Create auth_config.go with AuthConfig struct\n167: - [ ] Add environment variable parsing for new config options\n168: - [ ] Add validation for issuer/audience claims\n169: \n170: ### Phase 2: Enhanced Middleware\n171: - [ ] Create auth_middleware.go with enhanced MiddlewareFunc\n172: - [ ] Implement public path checking\n173: - [ ] Implement query parameter token extraction\n174: - [ ] Add issuer/audience claim validation\n175: \n176: ### Phase 3: Dynamic Key Rotation\n177: - [ ] Add SIGHUP signal handler in server.go\n178: - [ ] Implement hot-reload of public key\n179: - [ ] Add validation before replacing key\n180: \n181: ### Phase 4: Integration\n182: - [ ] Update server.go to use enhanced middleware\n183: - [ ] Update error response format for consistency\n184: \n185: ### Phase 5: Testing\n186: - [ ] Unit tests for public path configuration\n187: - [ ] Unit tests for key hot-reload\n188: - [ ] Unit tests for query parameter extraction\n189: - [ ] Integration tests with mock JWT tokens\n190: \n191: ---\n192: \n193: ## Acceptance Criteria\n194: \n195: - [ ] Public paths configurable via PICOD_AUTH_PUBLIC_PATHS\n196: - [ ] SIGHUP signal triggers public key reload\n197: - [ ] Query parameter token extraction works when enabled\n198: - [ ] Issuer and audience claims validated when configured\n199: - [ ] Error responses include error_code field\n200: - [ ] Key rotation is atomic (no race conditions)\n201: - [ ] Default public path /health works without auth\n202: - [ ] All existing functionality preserved (backward compatible)\n\n(End of file - total 202 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Proposal: AR-017 — PicoD JWT 中间件增强\n\n## Summary\n\nEnhance the existing JWT authentication middleware in `pkg/picod` with configurable public paths, dynamic public key rotation, and flexible token extraction. The enhancement improves the current auth.go implementation to better support production deployment scenarios.\n\n## Purpose\n\n### Background\n\nThe current PicoD service (AR-015) includes basic JWT authentication via `AuthManager` in `pkg/picod/auth.go`. The implementation loads an RSA public key from the `PICOD_AUTH_PUBLIC_KEY` environment variable and validates Bearer tokens on all `/api/*` endpoints. However, the current implementation lacks:\n\n- Public path configuration (endpoints that don't require authentication)\n- Dynamic public key rotation without service restart\n- Support for token extraction via query parameters\n- Granular error handling matching the router package patterns\n\n### Goal\n\nEnhance the PicoD JWT middleware in `pkg/picod` with:","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/proposal.md","time":{"start":1775857632488,"end":1775857632508}}}}
